{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_apple_ver01/data/sn83025812/00416156281/1930122601/0548.xml":{"full_text":"The Independent\nW. O. SAUNDERS, Senior Editor WM. K. SAUNDERS, Junior Editor\nPublished Every Friday in the Year by W. O. Saunders and his son,\nE. Colonial Ave., Elizabeth City, Pasquotank County. North Carolina.\nCeo. W. Haskeit, Superintendent of Plant\n-:i\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICE:?In the Counties of Camden, Chowan, Curri\ntuck, Dare, Gates, Hyde, Pasquotank, Perquimans, Tyrrell and Washing\nton $1.50 a year, $1.00 far 6 months, 50c for 3 months, payable in advance.\nElsewhere. $2 a year, $1.00 for b months, 50c for 3 months.\nEntered as 2nd Class matter at the 1'. O., Elizabeth City, N. C., June 9, 1908\nVOL. XXIII. FRIDAY, DECEMBER 26, 1930. MO. 1,205.\nWHO WRECKED THE BANK?\nI? >1 1 this fact stand out ahove all the excitement of the\npast week: I'. H. Williams, the so called \"threat finan-i\ncia! wizard\", was responsible for the wreck of the\nSavings Hank N Trust t o. Mr. Williams is not so smart: he\nlacks that fundamental qualitx that makes for good citizenship.\nJ community interest.\nMr. Williams has not huilt for Elizaheetli City: he has\nl?uilt for sell. Selfishh he invested his own inonev in the'\nstocks and bonds ,?f outside corporal ions. He advised and\nencouraged others in the community to do likewise. And it;\nwas tIt.^ inonev that miglii have remained in Eilxabcth A itv i\nI\nto work for the upbuilding of Elizabeth City that was with.- j\ndrawn from the vaults of the Savings Bank Trust Co.. leaving\nit moneyless. Mr. Williams is not <o smart. Bv his own ex-\n1 ample and advice lie accomplished the undoing of the financial\ninstitution which he headed. Short-siylued Mr. Williams!\n1 hese rich men who invest their money in stocks and bonds\nare as undesirable citizens as the miser who hoards his inonev in j\nj' an old sock. Mr. Charles Blades, a Mr. Pat Williams and!\nany one of a number oi other -o calied lug men of this tow n are\nnot worth hall as much to t!ic lown as the laboring man who!\ni puts his savings into a good sound bank where thev pav him\na lair rate of interest while working lor the conimtmitv in\nwhich he lives and upon the prosperity of which he depends j\nJ; for employment.\nj P. II. Williams has been an evil and vicious influence in'\nj _ the community. Let that statement sink home. Mr. Williams j\ninstead ot building up his bank and building up the eotnmunitv's j\n1 resources, lias been one of the most powerful influences at\ni work to drain the community of needed cash. And he sue-J\ncecded in wrecking his own bank, lie wasn't long-headed!\ni after all.\nit n\nn .oi the money m this conimtmitv were invested in\nI foreign >tocks and bonds. Elizabeth City and the Alb*inarle\nwould be utterly bankrupt. It i> the money that is kept at'\nJ liotne that the tiiotu-x m local circulation and that builds'\nhomes industries.\nIt is fortunate n>r Elizabeth City that the strength of its j\nj oldest and largest bank was subjected to a gruelling test in!\ni last Friday's panic. The First Citizens National Bank has jl\nj long- etijo;, ed the con idetice of its home people, that confidence n\nhas been immeasurably .strengthened In what happened here1\nI last week: penpic who never put their money in banks before'\nare bringing their savings the bank that has proved its\nstrength. I\nMoiiex in a good strong I:ank i> better than monev in a\nbond: it i-n't alwaxs ea>y to seli a b.,nd when xou need the\nmoney and it often happens that the bond for which vou pay!\nj SI0Q may turn out p, be wrtli much le-, than that when you lj\ni try to dispose ,.f Jt. }?t i(f in our tow n are holding I\nI* bonds to-day for which they wouid be glad to get ?75. j1\n1:1 terrible times the community without a consider-!'\nable ca-h reserve i> inviting bankruptcy. Keep vour monev j\nm your home bank and encourage your friends and neighbours!'\nto do likewise.\nOUR CRYING NEED j;\nIJJJL1 HiS newspaper learn- that our County Trial Justice.}]\n1 f*6^~ 10 Sawver ha- quarreled with County l'rose- j'\nr?j cutor, Larry Knnis Skinner. Jr. And when Judgej\nI Sawver strikes out at a man liis fang- tiil with venom. County ji\nProsecutor Skinner will have troubles enough in Sawyer s i\ncourt front now on.\nNo. %5-10 Sawyer long ag<> split with the Mayor and h\nJV>li<?e of Elizabeth City. Our police department can count on ji\nhint for no co-operation whatsoever and they frequently find\nthemselves thwarted in their efforts to apprehend and Vr'nkr 1'1C 1\ntown's worst criminals to justice. Sawyer has long- been at\nwar with the police and mi-ses no opportunity to ,embarrass\n?i them. i\nJudge Sawyer's court is a menace to the peace and security\nj| of every property holder in Elizabeth City. In Judge Sawyer j\nthe hoodlum, the bootlegger and the racketeer, all at war with\nII the police, feel that they have a friend. It is notorious that it is M\njl very difficult to convict certain types in Judge Sawyer's\njj court. An inevitable result of this terrible situation is that h\nElizabeth City is menaced by a growing underworld that is!\n?j becoming more vicious, more arrogant and more sure of itself.\nElizabeth City needs a police court, independent of the j\nji county court and it- Sawyer gang. Since the Mayor and then\nj! police can get no cooperation from the County court, let the!1\ni Hoard of Aldermen come to the support of the Mayor undj,\npolice and a-k the (leneral A-sembly which meets in January j]\nj] to provide a police court for Elizabeth tit v. i(\nThe wings of this bird Sawyer can be nicely pinioned byt,\nj providing a city court and taking the prosecution of the city's i\ncriminals out of the County court. In the interest of law,\n>rder and public .-afety no time should be lost in shackling \\'o.\n963-10 Sawyer by establishing a new court. We might ask j\nthe (ieneral Assembly to provide such a court as an experi\n0 meat for a matter of two years only. It is going to take two j\nj years to relegate Sawyer to the shades of political oblivion j,\nwhere he belongs, and we can't afford to leave the adminis- j\nm\ntration of justice in his hands .-o much as two months longer. 1\nSawyer is in a nasty mood. lie must be squelched.\nDUMB BANKERS\nTT51 W AS talking with a Norfolk hanker the other day andj'\nVx'i he was expounding gravelv on the subject of panics. I\n\"I anic- come in cycles.\" he said: \"they come and they b\n1 go. This panic, like all other panics we have had. will run its |J\nI course and we will swing back intojanother era of prosperity.},\niniE> biivh.ii>!\nnow on we wiil see a gradual improvement with a highly visible j\nImprovement by early spring.\"\n1 asked the Norfolk hanker why do panics run in cycles?!\nI lie replied: \"It seems to he a law of economics which none of j\njus understand.\"\nThat is the tragedy of our limes; the big boys at the top j\nwho control the wealth and industrv of America are generally\nj about as dumb as tin friend the Norfolk hanker. I hey know,\nI that panics come and panics go. hut as for the causes, they\nj haven't enough learning and intelligence to tfomprehend: or,\nI if they have the comprehension, they do nothing about it.\nOur colleges and universities are busy turning out armies of\nbook-keepers and accountants and only accidentally producing\nan occasional economist. And the economist who emerges from\nour five-and-ten-cent-store type of educational mills is w ithout\nhonor because lie might as well try to expound the Kinstcin\ntheory of relativity to a Kotarv Ciub as to talk economies to,\nthe average American hanker and business man.\nA NUISANCE\nK you are having a Merry Christmas. go to it; hut don't\nstop ail'! count tin- cost, hortunateh feu people seem'\ncapable \"I counting costs, which mav explain tin ir\nmerrinieut. There can he little merriment for anv one who\nseriously contemplates the sordid extravagance of the run\nof the mill celebrants of i lirislnias.\nI liristmas had it* beginning in a pagan orgv and was\n?the occasion ol drunkenne** and gluttons among our pagan\nancestors before the K'oinan Catholic hurch came upon the\nwreck of the pagan world and tried o> >ub*litute a Christ Child\nin a manger lor a bibulous I'.acchu*. In spite of nearly i<.\\n\nthousand years ??f t hristianity. the pagan dea >>f \"nristnia\nprevails and there will he more fond and drink cu-niiie l thi*\nweek than at any other sta-.m. \\nd our shop keepers haw\ntaken advantage oj the madness ,.f ihe season to make it a\nspectacular merchandising event for Mm marketing of bauble*\nthat are palpably undesirable that thev are *tored out of\nsight at all other seasons.\n1 he hristmas spirit a> extolled in Poems. and sermon* am!\nportrayed in religious art i* beautiful iudee i. but I fear that\nthe beauty of Christ mas i* f-eii utl ndy *p,.ihd he the ugii\nness of its exploitation. To l.e perfectly candid, as I view the\nmadness oi the ??eason I aui eonineiled t'> voice a positive c.?r\nviction that t hri'sima* ha> become *o-:Hu!uiig ..f a damm-.j\nnuisance.\nby Arthur Brisbane\nImportant Questions\nProhibition Illegal!\nSewed in a Bear Sk?n\nStrange Motions\nLet those that torment themselves\nwith fuoh.-h fears, and |)i nnr ihe.r\nfears to interfere with bit-: and\nthe return of prosperity. ask :hem\nselves these quv-tions:\nHave we net had depressions bo\nfore? Did we not then think that\nthe end of the world was coming?\nDid not men go about -hakim tie ir\nheads, saying:\n\"Yes. but this is a different kind\nof depression; v.i never had any\nthing like this.\"\nThose that have been in bu-ini ss\na reasonable length of lime recall\nthe head-shaking, moaning and\ngroaning of 1907.\nHaven't there been good times\nsince 1907? Didn't busine..- \"piti:\nup.\" to put ii mildly, after 1907?\nHaven't we since then added hun\ndred.; of billions to the country's,\nwealth?\nAnd haven't we cot everything\nnow that we ever had?\nCould anything be more stupid\nhan talk and action of a kind harm\nful to business, to banks and other\ninstitutions upon which the pros-1\nperity of us all and every mark's\nemployment depend absolutely?\n\nnit uuiuiuy uisuussus nit' cu'cision\nof Federal Judge William T. Clark.\n*ho .says that prohibition isn't legal\nbecause the people didn't pass on it.\nJudge Clark is interesting to mil\nlions of men and women, although i\nthey may not know it, for he is one\nof the famous O. N. T. Clark thread\nfamily.\nJudge Clark's decision that pro-\naibiticn isn't legal will be reversed\nL>y the Supreme court, probably.\n\nEverything is comparative, even I\nsorrow. The head of a great bank\nin New York tells of a client \"with I\n:he saddest face I have ever seen in\nmy life.\"\nOne year ago this client was j\nsvorth at least sixty millions of do!- i\nlars. And today his fortune is re- j\n:iuced to not more than twenty mil-1\nlion dollars, \"And you can'\nimagine.\" sai dthe banker, '\"how\nthat man suffers.\"\nIvan the Terrible, czar ef Russia.'\nto subdue those that opposed him.!\ninvented queer punishments.\nOn one occasion he had a bishop.\nsewed up in a bear skin, and the\nbishop, in his bear skin, thrown to\na pack of half-starved dogs.\nThe bishop suffered horribly, of,\ncourse, but only for a few minutes.'\nHis total suffering amounted to;\nfar less than the sufferings of some'\nthat have seen their fortunes and\nthe results of their life work gradu-'\nally taken from them, bit by bit.',\nluring the past year.\nI\nHarvard sends reassuring news]\nabout this grand old earth, on which I\nmen have lived, according to Pro-i\nfessor Osborne, for forty million\ncontinue to live for at least a mi'.lii :i\nmill;* year more.\nOur me rolling domicile is cue\nv.vi: many motions. We all know\nthai i\" turns around on its axis. rolis\na: ??and tin* i:n in 3(15 days, and\nft;' fi.r..' through <paec accompany\ning sun on its journey. But\nmost of use forget about tlu man\nothei tnev.ic ns ol the earth.\nWe art clad *o learn from Har-\nv.trd that a tvceii. my-:prion shak\ning of the earth's cru-t was a ntotc\nment back and firth. rhythm:-.:! and\n.eguiar. steends to each s vitv\nAnd while the earth's crust vice- 1\nmove, it moves only t .vo ten-thou-\nsandths of an inch in either direc\ntion. the motion cont inning for many\ndays.\nWe should be very grateful that\nlittle hitman microbes can be safe\n:n whirling globe, twenty-five\nr tmand mil- s around, as heavy as\niho'ich it \\v. re made of solid t.\nwith hoi fire under our feet, and\nabsolute zero, more than 400 de\npree below freezing. ai! around us. 1\nMr. Cutler, president of the Und: d\nFruit company, says that we did a\nburin vs last year with Latin-Amer\nica ol more than two thousand mil\nlion dollars, whereas we ought to be j\ndcin: a business of ten thousand\nmillion dollars.\nIn the Caribbean countries, says\nMr. Culler, we reach fewer than 30 j\nper c. nt of the possible custom; j\nAmerican business nun, with the\nDepartment of Commerce loading.\nshould look into that ten billion\ndollar possibility. We need the\nbusiness. j\nI;\nFrance has banking troubles and j\ndeals wit hdoubtful bankers in a\ndrastic fashion. Thirty-live French i\nbankers are in jail, and 185 under\ngovernment investigation.\ni|\nGermany has found a way to make,\ndanger signals plain even for the l\ncolor blind. Drivers approaching a j\nrailroad track need not know the\ndifference between white and red.\nThe warnnig conies in flashes. While\nthe way is clear a white light flash- j\nes forty times a minute. When a j\ntrain approache sa re dlight is turn-\ned on and flashes eighty times to\nthe minute. 11\nThe train automatically switches j\nthe red and white lights on and off.\nCopyright 1930. by King Features\nSyndicate, Inc.*\nj i\nDr. Jacocks Accepts\nState Health Post\nij\nDr. W. P. Jacocks. brother of F.\nG. Jacocks. of this city, this week\ndt finitely accepted the post of North\nCarolina State Health officer, upon I j\nassurances given him as to \"secur-; I\nity of tenure and freedom to dove-.\nlop the organization in respect to jj\npcrsonell and program.\" j#\nDr. Jacocks, who at present is en- jj\ngaged in public health work in I\nTravancore, India, under auspices\nof the Rockefeller Foundation, was'fi\nat first reluctant to accept the post.\nwhich was offered him after the\ndeath of Chas. O'H. Laughinghou.se.\nj\nWorld's Largest Petri?\nThe largest pearl in the world, sn\nfar iijwafr W m*: *4\nWr.'JINT.SS OF SAVINfiA\nBANK AMD YiU'ST CO.\n(Continued from Page Two*\nhead and said. \"No, no; I don't want\nto draw it out?T just wanted to see'\nif it was here.\"\nWas Won p in ISO\"\nCol. W. T. Old. of the Seaboard j\nNational Bank of Norfolk, who was\nfor many years cashier of die First\nNational Bank of this city, say; the\nrun on the batik last Friday v;a.s not\na circumstance to the cris-s ire. d\nby the bank in the panic of 159.'b\nIn that year bank- were failing all\nover the country. There was no run\nof small depositors on the First Na\ntional. but largo dej a.itors end ev n\nstockholders in the bank w: rr quiet\nly wididrawing their depori's and\nhiding them away. I'll twl you.\"\nsays Col. Old. \"Mr. Robin 0.1 ifhc\n?ate persident of die First dz\nCiti/ensi and myself'weal c! blood\nin tiiose trying days. But he public\nnever knew how close wc cai.i to\nhaving to clone our dcors.\niVuhdrevv S-ICJ.lrlf\"\nOne Pasquciank County family\ncame to town Friday n'.t ruing r.ul\nwithdrew lii\" savin ss of il.r end re\nfamily amounting; to S-PjatOC. An\ndien \".cut out on the strict and\ntalkid about it. Tlvv nvi.-s lit e\ncome uneasy with to niu:h money\n0.1 t h( ir hands that night. b (aire\nth.ey came btuk tits! '.rdrpf -it;i t\n?ii tki bank ins.: day. didn't k.s-v.\nthere was so much earh mom\nre in Pasqucs ank Conwy,\" a\ncue prominent lo.. i bu-.n man\nWinn he Irum .1 of thi., r.n rural\nfamily withdrawin -5-tO.ii .J from a\nMjs c bank.\nSavbr;.: Dejir.-iie.r.; Lor ?!.00(i\nh i\nChurns \"aiiona! who .-utciinib ci\nt